How internally @Transactional Internally works:

        ->Spring create a proxy, or manipulates the class byte-code,
          to manage the creation, commit, and roll back of the transaction
        ->If we have a method like callMethod and we mark it as @Transactional, spring
          will wrap some transaction management code around the invocation @Transactional method called

          Ex: createTransactionIfNecessary();
               try{
                    createEmployee();
                    commitTransactionAfterReturning();
               }catch(Exception e){
                    rollbackTransactionAfterThrowing();
                    throw exception;
               }


Note:

 ->if @Transactional used at class level and method level the method level will get highest preference
 ->The @Transactional annotation does not work on private methods by default in Spring.
    This is because Spring's default AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming) mechanism uses
    dynamic proxies, which can only intercept external calls to public methods

1)Propagation:
   This defines how the transaction boundary can be managed when we one method having @Transactional
   annotation which calls another method which is having @Transactional annotation

   Types:
    1)REQUIRED  (Default One)
    2)REQUIRES_NEW
    3)NESTED
    4)SUPPORTS
    5)NOT_SUPPORTED
    6)MANDATORY
    7)NEVER


1)REQUIRED :
    ->This is the default one
    ->For this the method required a transaction if its having the transaction it will use if
      its not have means it will create a new one
    ->If exception occurs, both transactions, parent and child will be rolled back as they both
      use same physical transaction

Ex: @Service
