->Here we have already @Transactional annotation at "createEmployee"
    so when the "createAddress" method called it will be used the existing transaction
->Suppose we dont have an @Transactional at  "createEmployee" then it will create a new transaction
    at "createAddress" method

2)REQUIRES_NEW :
   ->It create a new transaction every time.
   ->Here spring suspends the current transaction if it exists, and then create a new one.
     It instructs the spring container to always create a new inner physical transaction and
     inherit an outer physical transactions characteristics

Ex: @Service
    public class EmployeeService{

        @Autowired
        private EmployeeRepo employeeRepo;

        @Autowired
        private AddressService addressService;

        @Transactional //  method level
        public Employee createEmployee(Employee employee){
            Employee employee = employeeRepo.save(employee);
            Address address = new Address();
            address.setId(1l);
            address.setName("Bangalore");
            address.setEmp(employee);
            addressService.createAddress(address);
            return savEmployee:
        }
    }


    @Service
    public class AddressService{
        @Autowired
        AddressRepo addressRepo;

        @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED_NEW) // required_new
        public Address createAddress(Address address){
            return addressRepo.save(address);
        }
    }

3)NESTED :
  -> NESTED acts like REQUIRED, only it uses savepoints between nested invocations
  -> Spring checks if transactions exists, and if so, it marks a save point. This means
     that if our business logic execution, then the transaction rollbacks to this save point.
     If theres no active transactions, it works like REQUIRED

Ex:      @Service
         public class EmployeeService{

             @Autowired
             private EmployeeRepo employeeRepo;

             @Autowired
             private AddressService addressService;

             @Transactional //  method level
             public Employee createEmployee(Employee employee){
                 Employee employee = employeeRepo.save(employee);
                 Address address = new Address();
                 address.setId(1l);
                 address.setName("Bangalore");
                 address.setEmp(employee);
                 addressService.createAddress(address); // add save checkpoints here
                 return savEmployee:
             }
         }


         @Service
         public class AddressService{
             @Autowired
             AddressRepo addressRepo;

             @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.NESTED) // required_new
             public Address createAddress(Address address){
                 return addressRepo.save(address);
             }
         }

         if any exception in throws in addressservice then the roll back will happens till save checkpoints



4)MANDATORY
   -> It will not create any new transaction but it will throw an exception if transaction not found means

Ex:      @Service
         public class EmployeeService{

             @Autowired
             private EmployeeRepo employeeRepo;

             @Autowired
             private AddressService addressService;

             @Transactional //  method level
             public Employee createEmployee(Employee employee){
                 Employee employee = employeeRepo.save(employee);
                 Address address = new Address();
                 address.setId(1l);
                 address.setName("Bangalore");
                 address.setEmp(employee);
                 addressService.createAddress(address); // add save checkpoints here
                 return savEmployee:
             }
         }


         @Service
         public class AddressService{
             @Autowired
             AddressRepo addressRepo;

             @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.MANDATORY) // required_new
             public Address createAddress(Address address){
                 return addressRepo.save(address);
             }
         }

      Here if employeeService is not having transaction annotation means it will throw an exception
      Exception : IllegalTransactionStateException : No existing transaction found for transaction

5)NEVER:
   -> If any transaction found means it will throw an exception.
   ->This states that no physical transaction should exist. if a physical transaction is found.
      then NEVER will cause an exception as follows org.springframework.transaction.
      illegalTransactionStateException : Existing transaction found for transaction marked with propagation "never"
